AGI - Pozzolo "white in face and completely in shock", which obsessively repeats "but can I have shot?" But also Pozzolo "altered by alcohol consumption" or "reassigned" in front of the carabinieri. Many and rich in nuances are the descriptions of the behavior of the deputy of Brothers of Italy protagonist of the story of the shoot at the New Year's Eve at the Pro Loco di Rosazza which are contained in the minutes of the statements issued by the witnesses, both to the carabinieri in the immediateness of the facts and in the days after before the magistrates of the prosecutor of Biella that on 5 April last provided to the same Pozzolo notice of conclusion of the investigations.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
To describe the MP as prey to a sort of catalyst after the shooting, is in particular the undersecretary to justice Andrea Delmastro. Answering the 8th of January last to the prosecutor Teresa Angela Camelio (who will soon leave Biella to go to lead the office of the pm of Pisa)&nbsp; and to the deputy Paola Francesca Ranieri with the Marshal Alessandro Sabatini, commander of the carabinieri of Andorno Micca, the undersecretary remembers that at the time when he returned to the room (he was on the outside to have heard a few near In particular, I remember that he was sitting in the middle of the table, with his back facing the table. After that he definitely got up and I think that was the time when Campana told him why you did it? In particular, I remember that Pozzolo was behind me when Campana spoke to him, but Pozzolo did not answer him in any way." At that point, the investigator would have approached the undersecretary "white in his face and completely in shock," he said, "but can I have fired?" two or three times, he was catatonic."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"Sincertainly - says Delmastro - I didn't know what to tell him and I didn't answer him." If the undersecretary points out that "I didn't get the impression that (Pozzolo - ndr) was brilliance or 'before', another witness explicitly describes an obvious state of drunkness of the MP. It's Maverick Morello, son of Delmastro's head coach. Morello, describing the moment that Pozzolo was introduced to him, tells the Carabinieri "I felt that he was altered by alcohol intake"; opinion shared by his sister Valentina Morello, wife of Luca Campana, the 31-year-old wounded by the gun, who puts in record that in his opinion Pozzolo was "evidently altered, I think after the alcohol intake". And Maverick also points out that during the journey made to transport Campana to the ambulance, Pozzolo "has tripped at least two three times dangerously, probably because of his state of drunkenness". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the notice of closing the investigation, the Prosecutor Camelio explains clearly that even the ballistic technical advice, carried out by the expert Raffaella Sorropago, "has ascertained the full supposition of the narrative of people informed about the facts and in particular those of the offended person and did not find the alternative reconstruction originally provided by Mr Pozzolo at the time of the facts". A contradiction, that between the tale of Pozzolo and that of all other witnesses regarding the "movements" of the weapon, which emerges up to the first summary minutes collected by the carabinieri in the night at the Pro Loco di Rosazza. Pozzolo releases a spontaneous statement in which he says that "my jacket was rested on a chair and in taking it from the inner pocket fell on the ground the revolver; in confusion someone despite my repeated statements directed to communicate that the object of which it dealt duly guarded and unloaded was an effective weapon, evidently loaded raising the dog of the revolver itself and crushing the trigger of the same caused the expulsion of a bullet". It is the version to which the MP continued to remain faithful, but that, according to the magistrates, he did not find feedback in the technical peripheries.
All other witnesses tell a different dynamic. Starting with the head coach Pablito Morello who put it to the record as "Pozzolo Emanuele extracted from the inside pocket of his jacket a small drum-sized gun and rested it on the table of the main room showing it to the present and after handling it turning it between his hands exploded inadvertently a blow that went to hit the Campana leg" Luca Zani, municipal councilman of&nbsp;Fratelli d'Italia And that the gun came out of Pozzolo's trousers pocket, the injured man Luca Campana, who puts it on record: "Pozzolo pulled out of the right pocket of the pants a small revolver gun according to me to show it to be present because it kept it on the right hand palm." As he testifies all the other present who have seen the gun appear extracted from the Pozzolo pants pocket. A contradiction that immediately jumps into the eyes of the carabinieri who in the morning report of January 1 write that the spontaneous statements issued by Pozzolo are "completely discordant with those provided by witnesses. In particular, he reported that his weapon had accidentally fallen from the pocket of his jacket that was leaning on a chair and that someone unidentified by him loaded it and exploded a blow." A discordance verified in the technical periciousness of the proxy is one of the elements that demonstrate the responsibility of the MP.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
At the New Year's Eve, as it was immediately established, there were also several children. A circumstance that has made to reflect on the escaped danger in the circumstance of Campana's wound. From the minutes of the testimony of the witnesses, emerges a case in particular, that of the daughter of Davide Zappala', councilor to the Municipality of Biella, friend and faithful of Andrea Delmastro, present at the event with the wife and child of 4 years. "At one and a half," said Zappala, "my wife entrusted me with my daughter, who was very tired in the late hour. I sat her on the green chairs next to the table where I shot him." The little girl was just over a meter away from where the gunshot that then hit Campana exploded. "After having sat my daughter," Zappala continued, "I went to the table next to the main kitchen i.e. front of the entrance to the hall and I noticed Campana Luca dancing probably near this table; At the same time I noticed a group of people near the table where the shot took place." The table, as Zappala specifies, is the one where the child was. "At that point - the testimony continues - I heard the shot I turned and I saw Campana heading towards the kitchen; I followed him and noticed that he lowered his pants, sat in a chair of the secondary kitchen and noticed a hole on his thigh. After I have a mental blackout: I remember Pozzolo in shock that he sat in the green chair where shortly before I had sat my daughter." "Subject after the shooting - it's the end of the story - my wife looked for my daughter. She was worried. She saw the real girl. She was afraid she was impressed. She cried because she feared the worst."
